<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="PubMed-not-MEDLINE" Owner="NLM"><PMID Version="1">41414438</PMID><DateRevised><Year>2025</Year><Month>12</Month><Day>19</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1094-4087</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>33</Volume><Issue>25</Issue><PubDate><Year>2025</Year><Month>Dec</Month><Day>15</Day></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Optics express</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Opt Express</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Generation of sub-50 fs, 1.3 &#x3bc;J, 110&#x2005;GHz pulse burst in a gain-managed nonlinear Yb-doped fiber amplifier.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>52677</StartPage><EndPage>52685</EndPage><MedlinePgn>52677-52685</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1364/OE.582319</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText>We demonstrate a compact burst-mode fiber laser capable of generating ultrashort pulse trains with intra-burst repetition rates exceeding 100&#x2005;GHz. Stable high-frequency burst operation is achieved through a 45&#xb0; fusion splice between polarization-maintaining fibers. Based on gain-managed nonlinear amplification, the system delivers a 1.3 &#xb5;J burst energy consisting of eight 43 fs sub-pulses, with a 26 W average power at a 20&#x2005;MHz burst repetition rate. To the best of our knowledge, this represents the highest intra-burst repetition rate achieved for sub-50 fs pulses from a fiber laser. The proposed laser exhibits great potential for high-throughput and high-precision micromachining.</AbstractText></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Wang</LastName><ForeName>Yu</ForeName><Initials>Y</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Pang</LastName><ForeName>Yuxi</ForeName><Initials>Y</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Xiu</LastName><ForeName>Longwang</ForeName><Initials>L</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Hu</LastName><ForeName>Xinyu</ForeName><Initials